Product Requirement Document (PRD) Addendum: Dynamic Behavioral Triggers for AI Study Coach
Status: Ready for Implementation
Author: Product Lead
Target Stack: Next.js 16 (App Router), Supabase (Postgres + Auth), Groq API via Vercel AI SDK, Zustand.
1. Feature Overview & Objectives
This PRD specifies the implementation requirements for Dynamic Behavioral Triggers within the SpaceLinear AI Study Coach ecosystem.
Rather than relying purely on user-initiated chat messages, the AI Coach will dynamically adapt its persona, state, and messaging logic based on real-time data states, operational triggers, and user interaction histories (e.g., initial setup status, bulk syllabus uploads, or recurring subject friction).
The primary objective is to transform the assistant into a context-aware co-pilot that proactively guides the user using the Feel-Good Productivity framework precisely when they hit specific study checkpoints.
2. Trigger Classifications & Behavioral Specifications
The engine must monitor and react to three specific contextual interaction scenarios:
Trigger A: The First-Time Setup (Onboarding Variant)
Context Condition: Fired automatically when a user opens the chat panel and the system detects that the user's subjects table count is equal to 0.
AI Coach Behavior: * The coach bypasses passive greeting loops and takes complete control of the conversation.
It must issue an energetic, high-impact prompt asking the user directly about the number of subjects they are managing and what core topics need an immediate structural breakdown.
Tone Requirement: High-energy, collaborative, welcoming, and administrative-focused.
Trigger B: The Syllabus Dump & Auto-Scaffold (Agentic Variant)
Context Condition: Fired when a user inputs a list of multiple tasks, a dense string of notes, or a pasted curriculum syllabus into the text field.
AI Coach Behavior:
The coach intercepts the user's string before processing database executions.
It forces a conversational checkpoint requiring the user to explicitly define one "Daily Adventure" (the highest-leverage topic choice) and two "Side Quests" (health or relationship breaks).
It prompts the user to apply the 3 Ps framework (Play, Power, People) to their primary technical topic.
Agentic Hand-off: Upon minimal user validation or acknowledgment of these goals, the AI activates its createSubject and createTopic tools to automatically seed the database rows into Supabase.
Trigger C: Procrastination & The Wall (Friction Variant)
Context Condition: Triggered under two specific states:
The user types keywords indicating frustration or inertia into the chat interface (e.g., "stuck," "overwhelmed," "procrastinating").
The application front-end detects that a specific topic has recorded multiple consecutive relearn logs in the review_history table.
AI Coach Behavior:
The system pauses standard study workflows and overrides the interface state with the Unblock Method.
It steps the user sequentially through diagnosing structural Clarity, mental Courage, and physical Inertia.
It challenges the user to initiate a 5-minute countdown (the dose of discipline) focusing exclusively on the top two lines of their MDX file.
It mandates that the user state or message their designated accountability buddy.
3. Technical Implementation Architecture
+--------------------------------------------------------+
|                      Client UI                         |
|   (Detects empty space, text dumps, or relearn loops)  |
+--------------------------------------------------------+
                           |
                           v  (Sends Action Context Payload)
+--------------------------------------------------------+
|               `/api/coach/agent` Endpoint              |
|        Validates Supabase Session & Checks Counts      |
+--------------------------------------------------------+
                           |
                           v  (Appends Specialized System Prompt)
+--------------------------------------------------------+
|                        Groq AI                         |
|    Switches behavior dynamically based on context payload|
+--------------------------------------------------------+
3.1 Endpoint Context Enrichment
The Next.js API route handler must perform server-side telemetry aggregation right before evaluating messages with the Groq API. The prompt constructor payload must be dynamically mutated as follows:
TypeScript
// Example Context Payload Structure expected by the LLM system router
interface CoachContextPayload {
  triggerType: 'ONBOARDING' | 'SYLLABUS_DUMP' | 'FRICTION' | 'STANDARD';
  activeTopicId?: string;
  consecutiveRelearnCount?: number;
}
System Prompt Modification Rule: If triggerType === 'FRICTION', the system instruction string must prioritize the injection of the Unblock Method guidelines over traditional educational chat formatting, keeping conversational tokens highly focused on mitigation.
4. UI/UX Interaction Requirements
Inline Tool Status Logging: While executing Trigger B (Syllabus Dump), the chat panel component must explicitly intercept the active tool call array and render localized, micro-feedback states ("⚙️ Initializing Subject...") so the user visually sees the layout being scaffolded.
Interface Overlays: For Trigger C (The Wall), the user interface can optionally illuminate a distinct highlight boundary around the text container, visually cueing the user that they have transitioned from standard review parameters into a focused, 5-minute unblocking milestone.
Cache Refresh Hooks: Upon completion of agentic tools triggered via any behavioral workflow, the frontend client must intercept the generation stream's onFinish block to invalidate old local caches, populating new entities inside the client view seamlessly.